## Routing & Pages

| Route | File | Notes |
|-------|------|-------|
| `/` | `pages/index.js` | `getStaticProps` passes `latestPost` (posts[0]) to HomeSection |
| `/work` | `pages/work.js` | Static |
| `/studio` | `pages/studio.js` | Static |
| `/timeline` | `pages/timeline.js` | Static |
| `/blog` | `pages/blog.js` | `getStaticProps` calls `getAllPosts()` |
| `/blog/<slug>` | `pages/blog/<slug>/index.mdx` | Bypasses SiteLayout ‚Äî BlogPost has its own layout |

---

## Navigation & Dial

The site uses a **mode-dial** as its primary navigation. The dial is a circular draggable element rendered in `SiteLayout` ‚Äî always on screen, fixed-positioned.

- **Modes**: `home`, `studio`, `work`, `blog`, `timeline` (defined in `data/siteData.js`)
- **Routing**: `useDial` maps mode IDs ‚Üî routes via `ROUTE_TO_MODE` / `MODE_TO_ROUTE`
- **Transitions**: Navigation uses the **View Transition API** (`document.startViewTransition`) with a fallback to `router.push`. CSS `view-transition-name` is set on `.mode` and `.dial`.
- **Scroll-link**: On the home page, `useDial` listens to the `#mode-home` scroll container and updates `--home-scroll` CSS variable via `requestAnimationFrame`, moving the dial up in sync with scroll. The dial's CSS `transition` is suppressed during active scroll (`.no-transition` class) and restored 150ms after scroll stops.
- **Keyboard**: Arrow keys navigate between modes in ORDER sequence.
- **Wheel**: Scrolling on the dial itself steps through modes.

